Gemini said
It looks like you’ve got a solid foundation! You're hitting that classic "automation itch" where you want your custom logic to feel like a native system command.

Since you're on Hyprland and using Pixi, you have a few ways to turn that "junk/scripts" folder into a professional-grade CLI suite. Here is how to bridge the gap from pixi run to just typing hello from any terminal.

1. The "Pixi Native" Way: Global Aliases
Pixi has a built-in way to expose tasks or dependencies globally. However, for a custom script like hello.py, the cleanest approach is to define an executable in your environment and link it.

In your pixi.toml, you can use the [tasks] section, but to call it from anywhere without being in that directory, you should utilize pixi global.

The symlink trick
If you want to keep your project structure as is, the fastest "Linux-y" way is to create a symlink in a directory that is already in your $PATH (like ~/.local/bin).

Make your script executable:
chmod +x ~/junk/scripts/mytools/hello.py

Create a wrapper script in ~/.local/bin/hello:

Bash
#!/bin/bash
pixi run --manifest-path ~/junk/scripts/mytools/pixi.toml hello "$@"
Make the wrapper executable:
chmod +x ~/.local/bin/hello

Now, typing hello Ghost anywhere will trigger the pixi environment, load the dependencies, and run the script.

2. The "Modern CLI" Way: Python Entry Points
If you plan on adding more tools, you should treat your mytools folder like a real Python package. This makes it much easier to manage as it grows.

Update your pixi.toml
Add a [feature.main.tasks] or simply a more robust task definition. Even better, you can use pyproject.toml style within Pixi.

Use pixi global install (Self-Referential)
You can actually install your own local directory as a global tool.

Add an [environments] section to your pixi.toml.

Run:

Bash
pixi global install --manifest-path ~/junk/scripts/mytools/pixi.toml my-tools
Note: This usually works best when your project is structured as a proper Python package with a pyproject.toml.

3. The Hyprland Integration
Since you're on Hyprland, you probably want this "centralized command line" to be accessible via keybinds or system status bars (like Waybar).

Keybinding your script
Add this to your hyprland.conf:

Code snippet
# Press Super + G to run your hello script in a popup terminal
bind = $mainMod, G, exec, ghostty -e bash -c "pixi run --manifest-path ~/junk/scripts/mytools/pixi.toml hello; read"
Recommended Folder Structure
As you move from junk/ to a permanent home, I'd suggest this layout:

Plaintext
~/.local/src/my-cli/
├── pixi.toml
├── scripts/
│   ├── hello.py
│   └── weather.py
└── bin/  <-- Add this to your $PATH
    └── hello (shell script that calls pixi run)
Quick Fix for your $PATH
If you haven't already, make sure your local bin is in your shell config (.zshrc or .bashrc):

Bash
export PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"
