For a robust, future-proof, and flexible setup on Arch/Hyprland, skip the manual symlinks and wrappers.

The "Pixi-native" recommendation is to use Global Environments managed by a Global Manifest. This allows you to treat your local scripts as a managed system tool that Pixi handles for you.

1. Upgrade to pyproject.toml
While pixi.toml works, pyproject.toml is the industry standard for Python tools. It makes your project "installable" as a package.

In junk/scripts/mytools/, run:

Bash
pixi init --format pyproject
This will merge your settings into a pyproject.toml. Then, add an entry point so Pixi knows what command to create:

Ini, TOML
[project]
name = "my-tools"
version = "0.1.0"
dependencies = ["rich"]

[project.scripts]
hello = "hello:main"  # <--- This maps the command 'hello' to main() in hello.py
2. The "Future-Proof" Install
Instead of pixi run, install your local directory globally. Pixi will create a "trampoline" (a tiny, fast executable) in ~/.pixi/bin/.

Bash
pixi global install --path ~/junk/scripts/mytools
Why this is better:
Decoupled: You can call hello from any directory, even if you delete the junk/ folder later (after moving the source to a permanent spot like ~/.local/src/mytools).

Managed: Running pixi global list will show your tool. pixi global update will sync changes.

Hyprland Friendly: You can now use bind = $mod, G, exec, ghostty -e hello without worrying about paths or pixi run overhead.

Version Control: Your ~/.pixi/manifests/pixi-global.toml tracks all your global tools, making it easy to replicate your setup on a new machine.

One-time setup: Ensure ~/.pixi/bin is in your $PATH (Pixi usually adds this to your .zshrc or .bashrc during installation).

