To keep this future-proof as you add more scripts (e.g., a system monitor, a Hyprland workspace switcher, or a weather tool), use a Flat Module structure. This prevents your root directory from becoming a mess.

1. The Robust Folder Structure
Move your scripts into a subfolder with an __init__.py file. This tells Python "this is a package."

Plaintext
my-tools/
├── pyproject.toml
├── src/
│   └── mytools/
│       ├── __init__.py
│       ├── hello.py
│       └── sysinfo.py  <-- Your next tool
2. Update pyproject.toml
The key to flexibility is the [project.scripts] section. This is where you define your "commands."

Ini, TOML
[project]
name = "mytools"
version = "0.1.0"
dependencies = ["rich", "psutil"] # Add more as needed

[project.scripts]
hello = "mytools.hello:main"
sys-check = "mytools.sysinfo:main"
3. The "Editable" Install (Crucial for Dev)
Since you are actively writing these scripts, you don't want to re-install every time you change a line of code. Use an editable install:

Bash
pixi global install --path . --editable
Why this wins:
Instant Updates: You edit hello.py, and the hello command in your terminal updates instantly. No rebuilding.

Namespace Safety: By putting scripts in src/mytools/, you avoid naming conflicts with other Python libraries.

Ghostty/Hyprland Ready: Since Pixi puts the executables in ~/.pixi/bin, you can call hello or sys-check directly in your hyprland.conf without any cd or pixi run boilerplate.

Pro-tip for Hyprland: Now that hello is a real system command, you can use it in a waybar custom module or a tofi/rofi menu effortlessly.

